`viz_data` (`crates/steno/src/bin/viz_data`) is a standalone binary that turns `dict.steno` plus its parsed `TypedEntry` list into `out/viz-data.json`, the sole data source for the static `viz/index.html` tree browser. Depending on this subtree means running the binary and getting a deterministic JSON tree of categories/nodes/axes; nothing outside this directory consumes its internal types.

The pipeline is strictly two-pass, orchestrated by `main.rs` → `build.rs`: pass one (`insert_leaves`) flattens `TypedEntry` variants into one `Node` per stroke via `tree::group_key`, merging one-liner/multi-line variants of the same stroke; pass two (`group_leaves`, delegating through `grouping.rs` and `axis.rs`) buckets those leaves by tree position and splices in synthetic nodes — `sec:`-prefixed section nodes and `#{line}.{idx}`-keyed axis-choice nodes — into the same `node_order`/`nodes` maps that pass one built. Ordering inside pass two is load-bearing: `link_sections` must run before `apply_children`, since section nodes only gain their children once both exist in `children_of`.

Node/position identity conventions are shared and must not drift independently: `tree::group_key` (variant merging), `tree::position`/`section_parts` (the `cat:`/`sec:` synthetic-key format, single-space delimiter), and `axis::group`'s bucket-index scheme (`#{line}.{idx}`, where `idx` is a global bucket index, not a source line number) are all cross-referenced by `grouping.rs` and by `build.rs`'s category/root resolution. `comments.rs` is the independent upstream: it scans raw `dict.steno` text (not parsed entries) for `##`/`##>`/`###` markers, and `label_for`/`section_for` feed directly into both `build.rs`'s category assignment and `grouping.rs`'s section bucketing — a change to marker syntax must be reflected in all three.

`json.rs` is the terminal consumer of the `Tree`/`Node`/`Axis` shapes: its field set, order, and null-vs-omit conventions are hand-coupled to `viz/index.html`'s JS with no compiler check, so any `Node`/`Axis` field change must be mirrored there manually. Across the subtree, node/category emission order is always first-seen file order (never HashMap iteration order), giving deterministic JSON across runs — this is relied on by every child that writes to `node_order`/`category_index`.